Distributed biomanufacturing =E2=80=94 make anything, anywhere
What is the most advanced manufacturing system on Earth? One answer could b=
e Elon Musk=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Calien dreadnought [ https://substack.com/red=
irect/7732635b-9026-4883-bad6-e9b976a85d71?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7Gn=
A_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 the factory that ma=
kes the factory that makes the world's most advanced electric vehicle. The =
Relativity Space [ https://substack.com/redirect/9d0b4dc6-0d32-4f8b-bf86-fc=
68eacf1140?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ] platform for 3D printing rockets is another candidate. While both are =
impressive, synthetic biologists would have a different answer: cells.
Cells are programmable molecular factories capable of producing every aspec=
t of the biosphere that carpets our entire planet. That probably isn=E2=80=
=99t how biology was described to you in primary school, but it=E2=80=99s t=
rue. Despite our best efforts, we are still eons away from rivaling the ato=
mically precise machinery that Evolution has developed. Biological systems =
are adaptive, resilient, efficient, and beautiful.
The fundamental insight of synthetic biology is that our fastest path to vi=
able nanotechnology is to learn how to program biology. According to Drew E=
ndy, one of the pioneers of synthetic biology, the field is a sort of meta-=
discipline. The goal isn=E2=80=99t to make any specific product using biolo=
gy, it is to develop the tools and frameworks necessary to develop any biop=
roduct. In his talk at Zuzalu, Endy shared the vision that Atoms are Local =
[ https://substack.com/redirect/e6a02da7-6ed6-4418-ac11-b1deef447f27?j=3Dey=
J1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=E2=80=94we h=
ave a general-purpose manufacturing technology all around us, we just need =
to get better at programming it.
Here=E2=80=99s a tangible example: in the 1970s we developed basic tools th=
at let us copy and paste DNA. We discovered tools for cutting DNA at specif=
ic sites called restriction enzymes [ https://substack.com/redirect/90ed857=
c-37e7-46c6-b46f-9efd83e71258?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlX=
XepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Once we could cut DNA, we figured how to paste in =
new pieces using another type of enzyme called a ligase [ https://substack.=
com/redirect/c5e93ce1-5787-432a-9a19-30eba56737bb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb=
8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. With these tools, it became po=
ssible to mix and match pieces of DNA into new combinations=E2=80=94referre=
d to as recombinant DNA. This was a really big deal. Up until this point, t=
he only system recombining genes in new ways was Evolution. Now, humans cou=
ld too. The first =E2=80=9Ckiller app=E2=80=9D for recombinant DNA was synt=
hetic insulin. Genentech pasted the gene for human insulin into bacteria ce=
lls, programming them to produce it abundantly. The Swiss pharmaceutical co=
mpany Roche ultimately acquired Genentech for $47B in 2009.
In his talk at Zuzalu, Ginkgo Bioworks [ https://substack.com/redirect/288e=
2915-b789-4b28-86be-6cf1a7e0eed4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZj=
mlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] CEO Jason Kelly argued that we are now in the se=
cond wave of the biotech tools revolution. Building on our toolkit for mani=
pulating DNA, we have three new categories of important technologies:
Lab automation and AI =E2=80=94 we are transitioning from an era of bespoke=
 and manual experiments to a world with foundries full of robots and machin=
ery making millions of precise measurements. At the bits level, AI is a pow=
erful tool for modeling biology. While math helped us describe principles o=
f fundamental physics, AI may be a better tool for predicting the complex a=
nd nonlinear dynamics of cells. I=E2=80=99ve previously argued that biotech=
 is the physical domain that has benefitted the most from AI to date [ http=
s://substack.com/redirect/ba75ca86-e688-4418-ae2c-7a5cb8c9fa7b?j=3DeyJ1Ijoi=
OXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
DNA Synthesis and CRISPR =E2=80=94 restriction enzymes and ligases gave us =
the ability to shuffle around stretches of DNA. Now, DNA synthesis technolo=
gy makes it possible to write new DNA. CRISPR is a Nobel-winning advance [ =
https://substack.com/redirect/e9b995da-2b82-4e5a-9f2c-7e3634e9723a?j=3DeyJ1=
IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] that gives us =
=E2=80=9CGenetic scissors: a tool for rewriting the code of life.=E2=80=9D =
If we had only copy and paste before, CRISPR gives us the edit function=E2=
=80=94the ability to change specific bases of DNA programmatically. Imagine=
 curing a genetic disease by editing the dysfunctional gene back to a funct=
ional state.
Genomics =E2=80=94 Between 1990 and 2003, scientists around the world coord=
inated to produce the first reference map of the human genome [ https://sub=
stack.com/redirect/a222b148-e644-4ce9-87b0-26cd7c4cc87c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Q=
ifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=E2=80=94the set of geneti=
c sequences defining our species. This ambitious project cost nearly $3B. S=
ince then, DNA sequencing has decreased in cost faster than any technology =
in human history [ https://substack.com/redirect/2a1bfb58-a075-428b-8dd8-3d=
5e117ab7ca?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ], including computing. Companies are racing towards a $100 genome [ htt=
ps://substack.com/redirect/1124925b-b7c2-4dda-a788-c2f7549f3621?j=3DeyJ1Ijo=
iOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], which is absolut=
ely insane.
Copy, paste. Read, write. Edit, program. These aren=E2=80=99t analogies to =
information technology=E2=80=94biology is an information technology. As Kel=
ly would put it, =E2=80=9Cbiology is programmability for the physical world=
=2E=E2=80=9D As a scientist, I=E2=80=99ve bee=
n obsessed with building on top=20=
of this emerging tool stack. If you want to go deeper on this tech, I=E2=80=
=99ve written the 4-S series [ https://substack.com/redirect/5df5366c-0019-=
456f-a030-dfe15d7d2bf7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqO=
sa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=E2=80=94on Sequencing, Synthesis, Scale, and Software=E2=
=80=94that should serve as a solid starting point.
If insulin was the killer app for v1 of genetic engineering, what kinds of =
things can we build with v2? The loftiest claim for synthetic biology is th=
at the answer is basically everything. McKinsey estimated [ https://substac=
k.com/redirect/8fa627cf-aec1-43c2-8506-179c1fea1178?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.=
gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] that =E2=80=9Cas much as 60 p=
ercent of the physical inputs to the global economy could, in principle, be=
 produced biologically.=E2=80=9D So far, the four main verticals the indust=
ry has focused on are food, materials, chemicals, and medicines.
Several incredible examples were on display at the summit in Zuzalu:
Materials: Biomason CEO Ginger Dosier shared her vision to build a distribu=
ted network of bioreactors that grow cement using biology. Cement is the wo=
rld=E2=80=99s most used human-made material, so the transition away from ki=
lns would have a huge impact on reducing carbon emissions. Clearly, distrib=
uted cement production would be interesting for network states.
Chemicals: Jennifer Holmgren, the CEO of Lanzatech, told us about the synbi=
o-powered chemical plants they are building around the world to convert car=
bon emissions into products like fuels, proteins, and materials. They feed =
emission streams to microbes [ https://substack.com/redirect/49fde633-1fe0-=
466d-8191-9e49ff654262?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqO=
sa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] that spit out chemical products using their metabolic mach=
inery. Could network states one day crowd-source ownership of their own che=
mical plants?
Medicines: synthetic biology isn=E2=80=99t just applicable to planetary hea=
lth=E2=80=94it also has the potential to transform human health. Mark Kotte=
r, who is an academic neurosurgeon and the CEO of bit.bio [ https://substac=
k.com/redirect/2f51b845-2ce0-43b6-b67a-57cb22293b88?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.=
gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], told us about his vision to =
develop a new generation of medical therapies by reprogramming human cells.=
 Specifically, bit.bio is building a platform on top of induced pluripotent=
 stem cells (iPSCs), another Nobel-winning discovery [ https://substack.com=
/redirect/6d6db275-f6aa-41ce-9396-6c50cbe7d644?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5=
T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] that makes it possible to transfor=
m differentiated cells back into stem cells=E2=80=94the type of cell that c=
an then be transformed into any other cell type in the body. This vision di=
rectly overlaps with the longevity focus at Zuzalu.
Food: Agriculture is a critical module in the operating system of any moder=
n civilization. Jason Kelly highlighted several key strategic acquisitions =
[ https://substack.com/redirect/33f9e284-a38f-49eb-9192-f3b4bb095983?j=3Dey=
J1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] that dramati=
cally expand Ginkgo=E2=80=99s capabilities in this market. Mark Kotter also=
 highlighted the potential for the bit.bio platform to accelerate the growi=
ng cellular agriculture [ https://substack.com/redirect/245ccb91-c056-4f3f-=
b5e3-e6bf664f916a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6=
m8ExkRNpU ] market. So far, removing animals from food supply chains has be=
en an afterthought for industrial economies with entrenched processes. For =
new societies without almost 100 million cows [ https://substack.com/redire=
ct/fbfded91-1a64-4b22-9100-7213f3782f8b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Z=
lNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], this value proposition could be a lot mo=
re compelling.
It=E2=80=99s fairly obvious why a network state would want this type of tec=
hnology. If you could grow your own physical resources using distributed bi=
omanufacturing, this would accelerate progress towards total independence a=
nd sovereignty. Again, sovereignty is intimately connected to physical abun=
dance. Self-sufficiency could dramatically reduce the current asymmetry in =
negotiation with larger nation states.
This has the potential to be an equally beneficial opportunity for the synt=
hetic biology community. Historically, synthetic biology has gone through s=
everal funding winters, much like AI [ https://substack.com/redirect/91347d=
87-3589-41da-ae7a-9d252aa04e34?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjml=
XXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Some of the early businesses have struggled to be=
come cost-competitive with existing manufacturing systems on a time scale c=
ompatible with surviving as a startup. For chemicals, it=E2=80=99s hard to =
immediately compete with =E2=80=9Cworld-scale=E2=80=9D chemical plants on e=
fficiency and scale. In some ways, this pressure to deliver on an industria=
l scale has shifted the incentive away from biology=E2=80=99s superpower: d=
istributed biomanufacturing.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s hard to compete with existing industrial systems (at least ini=
tially) but it=E2=80=99s easier to produce small amounts of chemicals every=
where. As Drew Endy framed it, =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ve been trying to convinc=
e industrial states to build networked biotech. Could the story be differen=
t trying to convince network states to build networked biotech?=E2=80=9D
Here=E2=80=99s an intuition pump for one possible outcome: you will find es=
sentially zero credit cards in China. The reason for this is that China was=
 transitioning away from a cash-based economy [ https://substack.com/redire=
ct/19d1826c-110f-4f47-b3db-5d22623199aa?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Z=
lNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] when mobile phones were starting to becom=
e ubiquitous. They effectively leapfrogged economies with more mature banki=
ng systems en route to a cashless society where the majority of transaction=
s are digital. Could a similar story play out for network states and synthe=
tic biology? These new sovereignties may be more willing to experiment with=
 technologies on the frontier of manufacturing, which could lead to a first=
-mover advantage for establishing bio-based self-sustaining distributed sup=
ply chains.
The threads of blockchain and biology also intertwine in the inverse direct=
ion. As Jocelynn Pearl and I have recently outlined [ https://substack.com/=
redirect/bab005f4-6e43-4941-9eb6-bb9264904368?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T=
7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], some of our primary mechanisms for=
 funding and organizing scientific research are becoming increasingly ineff=
icient. Governmental funding bodies are showing signs of bureaucratic stagn=
ation, and research is primarily siloed within academic institutions.
One of the primary biomedical funding mechanisms increasingly supports (lit=
erally) senior researchers pursuing incremental ideas.
The growing Decentralized Science (DeSci) community seeks to use crypto to =
disrupt this trend. Can we use crypto capital markets to fund moonshot scie=
nce projects? Can NFTs be used in creative ways to simplify and accelerate =
scientific commercialization? Will DAOs help organize productive online res=
earch communities?
Decentralized Science =E2=80=94 expanding the aperture of research, acceler=
ating progress
Science is one of the most important public goods that society produces. Th=
e DeSci movement [ https://substack.com/redirect/5fb0c8d0-5054-4640-8ae4-ca=
abb91daa22?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ] =E2=80=9Caims to build public infrastructure for funding, creating, re=
viewing, crediting, storing, and disseminating scientific knowledge fairly =
and equitably using the Web3 stack.=E2=80=9D
One early piece of infrastructure for DeSci that is emerging is the IP-NFT =
[ https://substack.com/redirect/0eca3b26-0c65-4db9-80f9-d58775cfe93e?j=3Dey=
J1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], developed b=
y Molecule [ https://substack.com/redirect/d35a5696-c013-4a18-81ea-8d2ad4ba=
e1c9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. =
Intellectual property (IP) plays a foundational role in commercializing sci=
entific research. New patents are primarily generated by university researc=
h labs. If the patents have commercial potential, companies can negotiate w=
ith the university=E2=80=99s tech transfer office (TTO) to license the IP. =
University spin-outs are companies created to license IP and commercialize =
the new technology as a product. This is the current status quo, but the pr=
ocess has real inefficiencies and most IP remains dormant. Paul Kohlhaas [ =
https://substack.com/redirect/7bd39af7-6b49-4205-af7a-3040008836c7?j=3DeyJ1=
IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the co-founde=
r and CEO of Molecule, wondered =E2=80=9CWhat if instead of using NFTs for =
trading pictures of monkeys, we used them to solve a real problem like crea=
ting a more fluid IP marketplace?=E2=80=9D
The core IP-NFT protocol is a complicated piece of legal and technical inno=
vation, so it=E2=80=99s easier to get an intuition for the use case by focu=
sing on how early projects have been structured. The Scheibye-Knudsen Group=
 [ https://substack.com/redirect/1af6439e-f1e7-44ad-9ecf-4992f0792a78?j=3De=
yJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] at the Univ=
ersity of Copenhagen ran a large-scale analysis of the impact of prescripti=
on drugs on survival [ https://substack.com/redirect/04c0220d-f115-47fb-bb2=
8-800c564bf0d9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8E=
xkRNpU ] using a dataset of 1.5 billion prescriptions from 4.8 million indi=
viduals over 40 years in The Danish National Health Service Prescription Da=
tabase. They identified a set of over ten drugs correlated with extended hu=
man lifespan. Then, they minted this finding as an IP-NFT [ https://substac=
k.com/redirect/dcb45738-c1c1-4c50-a0ff-e284299a6a94?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.=
gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] using the Molecule protocol, =
which was then transferred to VitaDAO [ https://substack.com/redirect/d7059=
ea2-33d1-466b-91a4-5c50a6779fc1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjm=
lXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=E2=80=94a web3 community focused on funding longe=
vity research. This transaction will fund a new study focused =E2=80=9Con o=
ptimizing, repurposing, and re-formulating the 3 drugs with the strongest e=
ffect on human lifespan.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
And who is funding VitaDAO? Somewhat surprisingly, venture capitalists and =
even Big Pharma have been willing to interact with this community very earl=
y on. VitaDAO announced a strategic $4.1M  [ https://substack.com/redirect/=
23f223c7-7325-4660-8139-65c80d00e1c9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNu=
aMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]fundraising that placed Pfizer Ventures along=
side Shine Capital, L1 Digital, and Balaji Srinivasan. These extremely dive=
rse funders are making a bet that protocols like IP-NFTs and research commu=
nities like VitaDAO will succeed in establishing a new funding marketplace =
for high-quality early-stage biomedical research. In our lifetime, will the=
 IP for a blockbuster drug be financed on the blockchain?
Intellectual property still exists in the realm of bits, but crypto is begi=
nning to infiltrate the world of atoms, too An organization called LabDAO [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/4bb3d23f-b115-4892-a095-98cec7029c2c?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] is working to=
 build =E2=80=9Cthe science execution layer for Biotech DAOs.=E2=80=9D This=
 community is building a lab marketplace and set of computational tools to =
help these decentralized digital communities carry out their research.
Here=E2=80=99s the main idea [ https://substack.com/redirect/8f5f33e3-c32e-=
41b8-9a40-d3de789f32d6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqO=
sa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]:
LabDAO members build data and resource management software, in return for t=
oken ownership. The DAO interacts with physical labs (existing or new) by p=
aying to run experiments and providing data or materials to the token holde=
rs who funded the work. Data can be managed in an electronic lab notebook (=
ELN) on chain, using NFT datasets, for later licensing or use by third part=
ies. New labs can join the DAO to earn tokens for their services or to supp=
ort scientific progress by providing their methods at cost.
Start with simple, easily outsourced projects - =E2=80=9Cbit to bit=E2=80=
=9D projects requiring the user to supply data to be analyzed (e.g. bioinfo=
rmatics or screening experiments) and receiving data out the other side. Th=
en move to =E2=80=9Cbit to atom=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Catom to atom=E2=80=9D=
 projects.
They are trying to use the World Computer to increase fluidity between bits=
 and atoms. With infrastructure like the IP-NFT protocol and LabDAO in plac=
e, more science DAOs are starting to emerge. The range of interests is subs=
tantial, which is sort of the point. Looking through the DAOs on bio.xyz [ =
https://substack.com/redirect/2d44a1b2-06ba-4712-ac30-6770424c5fe1?j=3DeyJ1=
IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=E2=80=94a biot=
ech DAO accelerator=E2=80=94the projects range from longevity [ https://sub=
stack.com/redirect/d7059ea2-33d1-466b-91a4-5c50a6779fc1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Q=
ifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], to synthetic biology [ h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/628885ed-a8cf-4bf6-a9d9-f50f6a107e50?j=3DeyJ1I=
joiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], women=E2=80=99=
s health [ https://substack.com/redirect/1b1bd8fe-083b-4314-8b41-ed1f4c91c0=
e6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], or=
 even hair loss [ https://substack.com/redirect/02e1eaf5-ac71-42bd-a673-eee=
5ff8444ca?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ]. Yes, hair loss.
It doesn=E2=80=99t matter what the project is, the goal is to create a web3=
 toolbox for communities to mobilize around whatever they want to research =
and to actually make things happen.=C2=A0
One common question from web3 skeptics is: =E2=80=9CWhy does this require w=
eb3? Why isn=E2=80=99t HairDAO just HairLLC? We don=E2=80=99t need to reinv=
ent corporate structures and governance.=E2=80=9D After spending some time =
with various DAO communities at Zuzalu, I care less about this type of skep=
ticism.=C2=A0
Clearly, people from all around the world are deriving value from these new=
 tools for coordination, ownership, and transaction. Increasingly my mental=
 model of web3 is that it is a new set of Web protocols that has the potent=
ial to transform all of the energy stored up in hyperactive subReddits into=
 actual decentralized communities working to solve the problems they care a=
bout. The proof of the value of these new tools is the extent to which they=
 catalyze real action.
At Zuzalu, Paul Kohlhaas asked the question: =E2=80=9CStatistically, what i=
s the single largest determining factor in a person=E2=80=99s overall succe=
ss?=E2=80=9D The answer is: the zip code where you were born. This is espec=
ially true for access to science. As a scientist with the privilege of work=
ing at Stanford, I benefit from great funding resources, high-performance c=
omputing (HPC) resources, one of the best tech-transfer offices, and a circ=
ling swarm of VCs in the area.=C2=A0
The boldest version of the DeSci vision is to build the Web-native versions=
 of these resources: better funding mechanisms (IP-NFTs, etc.), better HPC =
resources and lab marketplaces using the World Computer (LabDAO, etc.), bet=
ter translational resources (the growing army of BioDAOs). I was consistent=
ly amazed by the diversity of this growing community in terms of both count=
ries of origin and training backgrounds.
If synthetic biology could offer network states a new level of physical vit=
ality and abundance, the reciprocal offer from the crypto community is to b=
uild the protocols, tools, and communities to spread access to science to e=
very corner of the globe.
As somebody embedded in the world of research and startups, I=E2=80=99m com=
fortable with the idea that our future will be very different from the pres=
ent. Frankly, I=E2=80=99m an accelerationist. I believe we should accelerat=
e progress in the physical world and use biotechnology to expand life=E2=80=
=99s presence in the universe [ https://substack.com/redirect/405e1afb-c0bf=
-4677-99d9-056178a8c96f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbq=
Osa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Still, my weekend at Zuzalu updated my priors on just ho=
w weird and different the future might be.
Outside of the nation-states that most of us inhabit, technologists are att=
empting to build totally new sovereignties. These network states and startu=
p cities will be the home to new types of political and physical experiment=
ation=E2=80=94and they may be some of the earliest adopters of our most adv=
anced distributed biomanufacturing solutions.
Just as scientists have solutions to offer to network states, DeSci is work=
ing to give anybody with an Internet connection the ability to participate =
in cutting-edge research. Perhaps crypto is =E2=80=9Cseeding a parallel uni=
verse with online communities=E2=80=9D but these communities hold the ideal=
s of permissionless entrance and community ownership. I, for one, will be f=
ollowing their progress=E2=80=94waiting to see the first moment where a med=
icine funded by a DAO delivers value in the clinic. What a time to be alive=
!
Departing from the Blockchain Meets Bio Summit [ https://substack.com/redir=
ect/d32b82b3-41eb-4308-97f7-73a018cace94?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_=
ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], I had a connecting flight through Istan=
bul, Turkey. As we flew into the city, the Bosporus Strait [ https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/c8023187-f6df-418f-8b24-15fdc31ce936?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ=
=2Egb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ] was visible out of the windo=
w. This incredibly narrow waterway forms part of the continental boundary b=
etween Asia and Europe. Walking around Istanbul, there is a palpable sense =
of being situated between bordering cultures. Swarming bazaars sell Turkish=
 delights and spices next to enormous Oriental lamps. The walls of ancient =
mosques are decorated with Christian murals=E2=80=94a direct repercussion o=
f the Crusades. Intersections are rich, vibrant, and complicated places. It=
=E2=80=99s still uncertain what will happen at the intersection of crypto a=
nd biology, but new threads and communities are being woven together. It=E2=
=80=99s probably worth assuming that the future will be way crazier than th=
e present [ https://substack.com/redirect/abbf3078-d690-485b-aaf6-0d38eb859=
68d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
